ge-pair-specific uncertainty baselines to account for varying hallucination tendencies across low- and high-resource languages. The impact of this work is threefold: (1) it prevents unnecessary degradation of non-hallucinated outputs, (2) it provides interpretable insight into when and why contrastive decoding intervenes, and (3) it sets a new paradigm for risk-proportional intervention in generative models. Evaluation will involve ablation studies on M2M-100 variants across 25 language pairs, comparing against standard CD, FECS, and DeHallucinator, with primary metrics focusing on hallucination reduction (via expert annotation), COMET gains, and human evaluation for fluency and adequacy.",
